## 5. Execution phases

Analysis of the DQ catalog reveals a natural ordering, each level acting as a *gate*
for the next. Phases are **ordered and configurable** (not hardcoded to two).

| Phase | Name | Example rule | Scope | Why it's a gate |
|-------|------|--------------|-------|-----------------|
| 0 | Readability | DQ-003 Readability/Corruption | FILE | pointless to continue if the file won't parse |
| 1 | Non-empty | DQ-002 Empty File | FILE | pointless to validate columns of a file with no data |
| 2 | Structure | DQ-001a Schema Structure | FILE | pointless to validate values if columns are wrong |
| 3 | Format + mandatory | DQ-001b Field Format, DQ-001c Mandatory Fields | CELL/COLUMN | schema conformance before business |
| 4 | Business | enriched rules (living catalog) | all | only meaningful on conformant data |

Gate rule: if a `BLOCKING` rule fails in a phase, the next phase is not entered; the
report indicates `stopped_at_phase`. `COLLECTING` rules do not block progression. A
`BLOCKING` rule whose errors are all `WAIVED` (exempted columns, cf. 4.4) is treated as
non-blocking.

